co.cask.coopr.spec.service

Class ServiceDependencies

  • java.lang.Object
    • co.cask.coopr.spec.service.ServiceDependencies

  • public class ServiceDependencies
extends Object
    Service dependencies define what a service provides, other services it conflicts with, install time dependencies, and runtime dependencies. See ServiceStageDependencies for a description of what types of dependencies can be defined at install time and runtime for services. Provides is a way for a service to say it satisfies the dependency it provides, and is useful when there are multiple services that provide the same sort of functionality. For example, an admin may create both a "mysql-db" and "oracle-db" that both provide the "sql-db" service. Some other service "app-server" requires a database, but does not care what type of database it is. This allows the admin to configure the "app-server" service to require just the "sql-db" service, which will ensure some service that provides the "sql-db" service to be present on the cluster. A service always provides itself. Conflicts defines other services that cannot be present on the cluster with this service. Real service names must be given here instead of "provided" names. For example, suppose service "myapp-1.0", "myapp-1.1", and "myapp-2.0" all provide "myapp". If another service "yourapp" is configured to conflict with "myapp", it will still be possible for "yourapp" and "myapp-1.0" to exist on the same cluster. Instead, the admin would have to configure "yourapp" to conflict with "myapp-1.0", "myapp-1.1", and "myapp-2.0".
